[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] This article is focused on providing clear, actionable guidance for safely deserializing untrusted data in your applications.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] However, many programming languages have native ways to serialize objects.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] These native formats usually offer more features than JSON or XML, including customization of the serialization process.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] Unfortunately, the features of these native deserialization mechanisms can sometimes be repurposed for malicious effect when operating on untrusted data.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] Attacks against deserializers have been found to allow denial-of-service, access control, or remote code execution (RCE) attacks.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] The following language-specific guidance attempts to enumerate safe methodologies for deserializing data that can't be trusted.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] Check the use of `unserialize()` function and review how the external parameters are accepted.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] Use a safe, standard data interchange format such as JSON (via `json_decode()` and `json_encode()`) if you need to pass serialized data to the user.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] If the traffic data contains the symbol dot `.` at the end, it's very likely that the data was sent in serialization.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] It will be only true if the data is not being encoded using Base64 or Hexadecimal schemas.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] If the data is being encoded, then it's best to check if the serialization is likely happening or not by looking at the starting characters of the parameter value.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] For example if data is Base64 encoded, then it will most likely start with `gASV`.
