[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] If there are data members of an object that should never be controlled by end users during deserialization or exposed to users during serialization, they should be declared as the `transient` keyword (section *Protecting Sensitive Information*).
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] For a class that defined as Serializable, the sensitive information variable should be declared as `private transient`.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] For example, the class `myAccount`, the variables 'profit' and 'margin' were declared as transient to prevent them from being serialized.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] Some of your application objects may be forced to implement `Serializable` due to their hierarchy.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] The `java.io.ObjectInputStream` class is used to deserialize objects.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] It's possible to harden its behavior by subclassing it.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] The general idea is to override `ObjectInputStream.html#resolveClass()` in order to restrict which classes are allowed to be deserialized.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] Because this call happens before a `readObject()` is called, you can be sure that no deserialization activity will occur unless the type is one that you allow.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] As mentioned above, the `java.io.ObjectInputStream` class is used to deserialize objects.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] However, if you don't own the code or can't wait for a patch, using an agent to weave in hardening to `java.io.ObjectInputStream` is the best solution.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-cheat-sheet] Globally changing `ObjectInputStream` is only safe for block-listing known malicious types, because it's not possible to know for all applications what the expected classes to be deserialized are.
