[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] Data which is untrusted cannot be trusted to be well formed.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] Malformed data or unexpected data could be used to abuse application logic, deny service, or execute arbitrary code, when deserialized.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] It is often convenient to serialize objects for convenient communication or to save them for later use.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] However, deserialized data or code can often be modified without using the provided accessor functions if it does not use cryptography to protect itself.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] Furthermore, any cryptography would still be client-side security - which is of course a dangerous security assumption.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] An attempt to serialize and then deserialize a class containing transient fields will result in NULLs where the non-transient data should be.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] This is an excellent way to prevent time, environment-based, or sensitive variables from being carried over and used improperly.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] The following is an example from Adobe’s BlazeDS AMF deserialization vulnerability (CVE-2011-2092).
