[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] It’s possible that behavior in custom deserialization protocols (for instance, by overriding `Serializable#readObject()` in Java) can be re-purposed towards malicious ends.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] Researchers have found complex object graphs which, when deserialized, can lead to remote code execution in most Java software.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] The next example is a denial-of-service attack against any Java application that allows deserialization.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] The `HashSet` called “root” in the following code sample has members that are recursively linked to each other.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] When deserializing this “root” object, the JVM will begin creating a recursive object graph.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] It will never complete, and consume CPU indefinitely.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] Many collection classes and object arrays can be manipulated in similar wasy, as they create their capacity prior to reading in elements, few sanity checks are performed.
[src:insecure-deserialization/deserialization-of-untrusted-data] It’s not like the JVM folks aren’t aware, they’re just hamstrung by backward compatibility with deployed code.
