[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:insecure-deserialization/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
